Could you elaborate a little on why this is required? it seems a bit awkward to be creating a Conflicts on the same service that this creates a dependency on, even if it does happen elsewhere.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Could you elaborate a little on why this is required? it seems a bit awkward to be creating a Conflicts on the same service that this creates a dependency on, even if it does happen elsewhere.
> 
> (and are there other side-effects if we stop the .socket when the .service is activated?)

There won't be any side effect. In fact, we should set the Conflict according to the systemd documentation.

> a socket file foo.socket needs a matching service foo.service if Accept=no is set. If Accept=yes is set, a service template foo@.service must exist from which services are instantiated for each incoming connection.
https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.socket.html

In our case, we set Accept=yes, so connection will be handled by systemd, spawning a new service instance for each connection instance. So we only need the obmc-console-ssh@.service. The service without @ means the connection is handled by the service itself, not systemd, which of course conflicts with the .socket file. That's why they added Conflicts=dropbear.service in OpenEmbedded dropbear.socket.
